":"Cullen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Declan, Dermot, Donal, Fergus, Aidan, Brennan, Donovan, Eamon, Eamonn, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cuileáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuileán’</i>, a variant of the personal name <i>Coileán</i> meaning ‘puppy’ or ‘young hound’ (see   Collin  ).","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cuilinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuileann</i>’, a byname meaning ‘holly’."],"variants":[{"name":"Collin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Leonide, Andre, Armand, Camille, Emile, Fernand, Firmin, Francois, Ghislaine, Normand.","English, French, Walloon, and Breton: variant of   Colin  . This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","German: variant of   Kollin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Cullinan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Cormac.","Irish (Clare): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cuileannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuileannán</i>’, from a diminutive of <i>Cuileann</i> (see   Cullen   2)."]},{"name":"Cullens","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Cullen  , with excrescent or genitival <i>-s</i>.","Dutch (Rotterdam): possibly an adaptation of English   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Cullin","meanings":["Irish (Longford and Roscommon) and English: variant of   Cullen  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":37,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":46,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":57,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":59,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Cullen II was born in 1512, in Bath, Somerset, England, his father, William Cullin I, was 12 and his mother, Emma Walwyn, was 29. He married llsa McMurdocke in 1545, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 1 September 1573, in Bath, Somer